ment. It asks what the law currently says about menstruation (spoiler alert: not much) and provides a roadmap for legal reform that can move society closer to a world where no one is held back or disadvantaged by menstruation. Bridget J. Crawford and Emily Gold Waldman examine these issues in a wide range of contexts, from schools to workplaces to prisons to tax policies and more. Ultimately, they seek to transform both law and society so that menstruation is no longer an obstacle to full participation in all aspects of public and private life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMenstruationxSocial aspects. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 7aLAW / Health.2bisacsh  aAdvertising.  aAdvocacy.  aAustralia.  aBathrooms.  aCOVID-19.  aCapitalism.  aCorporate philanthropy.  aDetention.  aDisclosure.  aEducation.  aEmployment.  aFem tech.  aGrace Meng.  aHomelessness.  aIgnorance.  aIndia.  aJails.  aKenya.  aLaw reform.  aLitigation strategy.  aLord Ayyappa temple.  aMenstrual Equity for All Act.  aMenstrual equity.  aMenstrual leave.  aMonica Lennon.  aNew Zealand.  aNon-binary.  aPads.  aPinky gloves.  aPlastic.  aPoverty.  aPrimary and secondary schools.  aPrisons.  aPrivacy.  aPrivate governance.  aProcurement.  aPublic buildings.  aSNAP.  aSabarimala.  aScotland.  aSouth Korea.  aState law.  aStigma.  aSustainability.  aTANF.  aTampons.  aTax.  aTitle IX.  aTitle VII.  aToxic shock syndrome.  aToxins.  aTrans.  aTransgender.  aUniforms.  aWomen’s health.  adata.  adiscrimination.  aequality.  agender.  alaw.  amenstruation.  aperiods.  ashame.  awomen.1 aWaldman, Emily Gold, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat